results.name: Number of knapsack factorizations of n.
comment: A knapsack factorization is a finite multiset of positive integers greater than one such that every distinct submultiset has a different product.

The sequence giving the number of factorizations of n is described as "the multiplicative partition function" (see A001055), so knapsack factorizations are a multiplicative generalization of knapsack partitions. - _Gus Wiseman_, Oct 24 2017
link: Vincenzo Librandi, Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..2000
example: The a(36) = 8 factorizations are 2*2*3*3, 2*2*9, 2*18, 3*3*4, 3*12, 4*9, 6*6, 36. The factorization 2*3*6 is not knapsack.
results.author: _Gus Wiseman_, Sep 26 2017
